est overseas owners of us agricultural land as of  smithfield had  employees around the world and an annual revenue of  billion the company was founded in  by joseph w luter and his son as the smithfield packing company now its largest subsidiary from  it began to purchase companies such as eckrich farmland foods of kansas gwaltney of smithfield john morrell murphy family farms of north carolina and premium standard farms the company was able to grow as a result of its highly industrialized pig production raising the animals using a vertical integration system of production that enables it to control the animals development from conception to packing thousands of livestock are permanently confined in barns with metal roofs known as concentrated animal feeding operations as of  smithfield raised  million pigs a year and processed  million producing over six billion pounds of pork it was the top pig slaughter operation in the united states in  at  pigs a day and along with three other companies slaughtered  percent of the cattle processed there until it sold its beef group in a smithfield sells its products under several brand names including cooks ham gwaltney john morrell krakus ham patrick cudahy smithfield and stefanos kenneth m sullivan has been the president and chief executive officer since  contents  company profile  pig production  vertical integration  housing and lagoons  pregnant sows  environmental and animal welfare record  emissions  use of antibiotics  operations in mexico  packaging reduction   humane society investigation  legal and labor issues  working conditions  union dispute  justice department penalty  philanthropy  sports sponsorships  see also  notes  references  further reading company profileedit the company traces its history to  when joseph w luter sr and his son joseph w luter jr opened the smithfield packing company in smithfield virginia the latter served as chief executive officer ceo until his death in  a grandson joseph w luter iii joined the company the same year and in  became chairman and ceo until smithfield was taken over by liberty equities in  the company hired luter again as ceo in  when it found itself in financial difficulties his restructuring of the company is credited with its improved performance his son joseph w luter iv became an executive vice president of smithfield foods and president of the smithfield packing company the parent companys largest subsidiary smithfield began to expand in  with its purchase of its main competitor gwaltney of smithfield this was followed by the acquisition of almost  companies in the pork beef and livestock industries between  and around  the company patrick cudahy was purchased in  and schluderbergkurdle in  in  smithfield opened the worlds largest processing plant a squarefoot facility in tar heel north carolina which by  could process  pigs a day smithfield purchased john morrell  co in sioux falls sd in  and circle four farms in  in  it bought two of the largest pig producers in the united states carrolls foods and murphy family farms of north carolina at that point the largest producer according to agricultural researchers jill hobbs and linda young smithfields purchase of these companies constituted a major structural change in the us pig industry farmland foods of kansas city was added in  as were sara lees european meats conagra foods refrigerated meats butterball the poultry producer and premium standard farms in  the company sold its  percent share in butterball in  for an estimated  million the acquisitions caused concern among regulators in the united states regarding the companys control of the food supply after smithfields purchase of murphy family farms the agriculture department described it as absurdly big as of  four companies—smithfield tyson swift  company and cargill—were responsible for the production of  percent of pork in the united states on may   shuanghui group also known as the shineway group the largest meat producer in china announced a purchase of smithfield foods inc for  billion shuanghui announced that it would list smithfield on the hong kong stock exchange after completing the takeover on september   the us government approved shuanghui international holding’s purchase of smithfield food inc the deal was valued at approximately  billion it was the largest stock acquisition by a chinese company of an american company as of  smithfield had  employees in the united states mexico and europe and an annual revenue of  billion it raises  million pigs a year producing  billion pounds of fresh pork and  billion pounds of packaged meat sold as  brands of pork products and  other foods along with specialty brands such as the paula deen collection and weight watchers the companys  core brands are armour carando cooks ham curlys foods eckrich farmland gwaltney healthy ones john morrell kretschmar margherita and smithfield the company also operates the genuine smithfield ham shoppe and a restaurant taste of smithfield both in smithfield virginia pig productionedit vertical integrationedit further information vertical integration in  the company bought hogfarming operations making it a vertically integrated company the system allows smithfield to control every stage of pig production from conception and birth to slaughter processing and packing—known as from squeal to meal or from birth to bacon joseph w luter iii said that this produces high quality consistent products with consistent genetics luter has said that vertical integration gives you high quality consistent products with consistent genetics and the only way to do that is to control the process from the farm to the packing plant according to tyya n turner the company obtained  pigs and the right to their genetic lines from britains national pig development company in  and used them to create smithfield lean generation pork which was certified by the american heart association for its low fat salt and cholesterol content according to luter it was vertical integration that enabled this housing and lagoonsedit the pigs are housed together in their thousands in identical barns with metal roofs known as concentrated animal feeding operations cafos the floors of the buildings are slatted allowing waste to be flushed into feetdeep openair pits the size of two football fields referred to within the industry as lagoons smithfield says the lagoons contain an impervious liner made to withstand leakage according to jeff tietz writing for rolling stone the waste—a mixture of excrement urine blood afterbirths stillborn pigs drugs and other chemicals—overflows when it rains and the liners can be punctured by rocks smithfield attributes the pink color of the waste to the health of the lagoons writing that the color is a sign of bacteria doing what it should be doing its indicative of lower odor and lower nutrient content pregnant sowsedit sows used for breeding are confined in  ft x  ft gestation crates this image was taken inside a smithfield facility in virginia in  smithfield said in december  that it would phase out gestation crates on its companyowned farms by  in the united states and by  in europe and mexico pregnant sows spend most of their lives in these stalls which are too small to allow them to turn around when they give birth they are moved to a farrowing crate for three weeks then artificially inseminated and placed back into a gestation crate the practice has led to criticism from animal welfare groups supermarket chains and mcdonalds smithfield said in  that it would phase out gestation crates by  but in  said it would not meet the timeline because of operating losses caused by the recession in january  it said that  percent of pregnant sows on its companyowned farms had been moved into group housing and out of the crates it would not commit to requiring its contract farms where almost half its sows live to phase out the crates environmental and animal welfare recordedit emissionsedit smithfield has come under criticism for the millions of gallons of untreated fecal matter it produces and stores in the lagoons in a fouryear period in north carolina in the s  million gallons of hog fecal matter were released into the states rivers workers and residents near smithfield plants reported health problems and complained about the stench of hog feces the company was fined  million in  by the environmental protection agency epa for  violations of the clean water act after discharging illegal levels of slaughterhouse waste into the pagan river in virginia its facilities in north carolina came under scrutiny in  when hurricane floyd flooded lagoons holding fecal matter many of smithfields contract farms were accused of polluting the rivers smithfield reached a settlement in  with the state of north carolina agreeing to pay the state  million over  years the company agreed to donate  million to clean up north carolina state university would receive  million to research the treatment of pig waste and the north carolina foundation for soil and water conservation ducks unlimited and the north carolina coastal federation would receive grants according to ralph deptolla of smithfield foods the company created new executive positions to monitor the environmental issues and hired dennis treacy a former director of the virginia department of environmental quality as executive vice president and chief sustainability officer treacy had previously been involved in the enforcement efforts against smithfield deptolla writes that smithfield also created an environmental management system esm launching it in  at its murphybrown facilities in  the company received iso  certification from the international organization for standardization for its hog production and processing facilities in the us with the exception of new acquisitions and in   plants in the us and  in romania received certification deptolla writes that  smithfield facilities were iso certified as of  in  its hogproduction subsidiary murphybrown reached an agreement with the waterkeeper alliance once one of smithfields biggest critics to adopt new measures to enhance environmental protection at the formers facilities in north carolina in  the company said it had reduced greenhouse gas emissions at its plants by four percent since  its processing emissions per  pounds of production by  percent and its firstprocessing emissions per animal by  percent smithfield attributed the improvements to the divestiture of the beef group in  it released its ninth annual corporate social responsibility report and announced its appointment of a chief sustainability officer and two sustainability committees use of antibioticsedit concerns were raised about the use by the company and its contractors of low doses of antibiotics to promote the pigs growth in addition to using antibiotics as part of a treatment regime the concern was that the antibiotics were harmful to the animals and were contributing to the rise of antibioticresistant strains of bacteria smithfield said in  that it would administer antibiotics only to animals who were sick themselves or who were in close proximity to sick animals however in concentrated animal feeding operations all pigs are in close proximity to each other operations in mexicoedit the earliest confirmed case of the hn virus swine flu during the  flu pandemic was in a fiveyearold boy in la gloria mexico near several facilities operated by granjas carroll de mexico a smithfield foods subsidiary that processes  million pigs a year and employs  people this together with tension between the company and local community over smithfields environmental record prompted several newspapers to link the outbreak to smithfields farming practices according to the washington post over  other residents of la gloria became ill from a respiratory disease in march that year later thought to be seasonal flu the post writes that health officials found no link between the farms and the hn outbreak smithfield said that it had found no clinical signs of swine flu in its pigs or employees in mexico and had no reason to believe that the outbreak was connected to its mexican facilities the company said it routinely administers flu virus vaccine to its swine herds in mexico and conducts monthly tests to detect the virus residents alleged that the company regularly violates local environmental regulations according to the washington post local farmers had complained for years about headaches from the smell of the pig farms and said that wild dogs had been eating discarded pig carcasses smithfield was using biodigesters to convert dead pigs into renewable energy but residents alleged that they regularly overflowed residents also feared that the waste stored in the lagoons would leak into the groundwater packaging reductionedit in  armoureckrich introduced smaller crescentstyle packaging for its smoked sausages which reduced the plastic film and corrugated cardboard the company used by over  pounds per year in  the john morrell plant in sioux falls sd reduced its use of plastic by  pounds a year and farmland foods reduced the corrugated packaging entering waste streams by over five million pounds a year smithfield packing used  percent less plastic for deli meat the company also eliminated  pounds of corrugated material a year by using smaller boxes to transport chicken frankfurters to its largest customer  humane society investigationedit in december  the humane society of the united states hsus released an undercover video taken by one of its investigators inside a smithfield foods facility the investigator had worked for a month at murphybrown a smithfield subsidiary in waverly virginia the associated press ap reported that the investigator videotaped  sows living in gestation crates according to the ap the material shows a pig being pulled by the snout shot in the head with a stun gun and thrown into a bin while trying to wriggle free the investigator said he saw sows biting their crates and bleeding staff jabbing them to make them move staff tossing piglets into carts and piglets born prematurely in gestation crates falling through the slats into the manure pits the video won a  webby award in the public service and activism category in response smithfield told the ap that it has zero tolerance for any behavior that does not conform to our established animal wellbeing procedures the company asked temple grandin a professor of animal husbandry to review the footage she recommended an inspection by animal welfare expert jennifer woods smithfield announced on december  that it had fired two workers and their supervisor at the companys invitation the virginia state veterinarian richard wilkes visited the facility on december  he told the virginianpilot that smithfield had been very responsive and very responsible in how theyve addressed the issues and that he had not seen any indication of abuse of the pigs and was impressed by their demeanor a humane society spokesman said that smithfield had provided the vet with a preannounced white glove tour legal and labor issuesedit working conditionsedit human rights watch hrw issued a page report in  documenting what it said were unsafe work conditions in the us meat and poultry industry in particular the report said workers make thousands of repetitive motions with knives during each shift leading to lacerations and repetitive strain injuries according to hrw the workers immigrant status may be exploited to prevent them from making complaints or forming unions the report cited working conditions in smithfield foods as an example according to the report the speed at which the pigs are killed and processed makes the job inherently dangerous for workers a smithfield manager testified in  during an unfair labor practices trial that at the tar heel plant in north carolina it takes between five and ten minutes to slaughter and complete the process of disassembly of an animal including draining cleaning and cleaving one worker told hrw that the disassembly line moves so fast that there is no time to sharpen the knives which means harder cuts have to be made with the resultant injuries to workers similar criticism was made by other groups about smithfield facilities in poland and romania union disputeedit agriculture history history of organic farming arab agricultural revolution british agricultural revolution green revolution neolithic revolution on land animal husbandry cattle pig poultry sheep dairy dryland extensive freerange grazing hobby intensive animal crop natural orchard organic ranching sharecropping slashandburn in water aquaculture aquaponics hydroponics related agribusiness agricultural engineering agricultural science agroecology agroforestry agronomy animalfree crop diversity ecology livestock mechanisation permaculture sustainable urban lists government ministries universities and colleges categories agriculture by country companies biotechnology livestock meat industry poultry farming agriculture and agronomy portal v t e the smithfield packing plant in tar heel north carolina was the site of a long dispute between the company and the united food and commercial workers union ufcw which had tried since the early s to organize the plants roughly  hourly workers workers voted against the union in  and  but the national labor relations board nlrb alleged that unfair election conduct had occurred and ordered a new election during the  election the company is alleged to have fired workers who supported the union stationed police at the plant gates and threatened plant closures in  according to human rights watch smithfield set up its own security force with special police agency status under north carolina law and in  arrested workers who supported the union smithfield appealed the nlrbs ruling that the  election was invalid and in  the us circuit court of appeals found in favor of the nlrb after demonstrations lockouts and a shareholder meeting that was disrupted by shareholders supporting the union the ufcw called for a boycott of smithfield products in october  smithfield countered by filing a federal rico act lawsuit against ufcw in october  the ufcw and smithfield reached an agreement under which the union agreed to suspend its boycott campaign in return for the company dropping its rico lawsuit and allowing another election in december  workers voted  to  in favor of joining the ufcw bringing the year fight to an end justice department penaltyedit in january  smithfield was assessed a  penalty by the us justice department to settle charges that the company engaged in illegal merger activity during its takeover of premium standard farms llc in  philanthropyedit the smithfieldluter foundation established in  is a nonprofit organization that acts as the philanthropic wing of smithfield foods dedicated primarily to providing scholarship opportunities to the children and grandchildren of smithfield employees it has given  million to christopher newport university in newport news virginia to establish the luter school of business and  million to the university of virginia cancer center in charlottesville virginia the foundation also provides support for its learners to leaders programs begun in  in sioux falls south dakota green bay wisconsin denison iowa and norfolk virginia sports sponsorshipsedit in  smithfield announced a race sponsorship with richard petty motorsports and driver aric almirola driving the  ford in the nascar sprint cup series the sponsorship was increased to  races beginning in  smithfield rotates its brands on the car featuring smithfield eckrich farmland gwaltney and nathans famous it is also the official food of richmond international raceway in henrico county virginia about an hour northwest of smithfield hq see alsoedit an american trilogy  fast food nation  food inc  pig business  notesedit  the other companies were american foods group cargill meat solutions and xl beef referencesedit  a b c d e f g h smithfield foods inc securities and exchange commission retrieved  may    a b c turner tyya  vault guide to the top consumer products employers vault inc p  isbn    a b woodruff judy who’s behind the chinese takeover of world’s biggest pork producer pbc newshour september    maduri frank j october   outside view chinas ownership of an iconic american food company upi   hettinger jonathan holly robert and meers jelter foreign investment in us farmland on the rise agopro july    a b c d e f g deptolla ralph smithfield foods smithfields journey to sustainability a work in progress global business and organizational excellence  septemberoctober   a b c d barboza david goliath of the hog world fast rise of smithfield foods makes regulators wary the new york times april    a b c tietz jeff boss hog rolling stone december    seward robert a regulations on meat hygiene in the usa in fidel toldrá ed safety of meat and processed meat springer    a b c d – – present– corporate officers smithfield foods undated  kenneth marc sullivan wh group ltd bloomberg  a b calamuci daniel return to the jungle the rise and fall of meatpacking work new labor forum  spring  pp – p  jstor   hobbs jill e young linda m vertical linkages in agrifood supply chains in canada and the united states research and analysis directorate strategic policy branch agriculture and agrifood canada june  p   company news smithfield in stock deal for tysons hog operations the new york times september    felberbaum michael smithfield to sell its stake in butterball associated press september    thomas denny  oran olivia  may  chinas appetite for pork spurs  billion smithfield deal reuters   saeed azhar  stephen aldred  july  exclusive smithfields china bidders plan hong kong ipo after deal – sources reuters   doug palmer us approves chinese company’s purchase of smithfield politicocom retrieved    a look back at the smithfield foods history our company and investors